<node id="Hypertension">
  <data key="d0">Hypertension</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Hypertension, also known as high blood pressure, is a medical condition characterized by consistently elevated blood pressure levels. It is recognized as a significant health issue due to its potential to lead to various serious complications, including cardiovascular disease if left untreated. Individuals suffering from hypertension are at a higher risk of developing additional health problems, notably those related to kidney health and diabetes.

Hypertension is particularly noteworthy as a common comorbidity among individuals with type 2 diabetes. In these patients, managing hypertension becomes crucial to prevent further complications, particularly as it can influence the progression of related conditions such as diabetic nephropathy. The relationship between hypertension and diabetes is complex, with hypertension also being a contributing risk factor for the development of diabetes and other noncommunicable diseases.

Overall, hypertension poses significant health risks, and its management is critical in maintaining overall health and preventing complications, especially in at-risk populations such as those with diabetes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-a07cef05efd947a538701b4c41b162b1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e1400e1158e4f7be2283a0366ebf4f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8e236a5eba0e1dbf843d32e509da045&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fd4cfbed43aa26af0eef694fecac2177&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eb1bc7614fcd68decf9461b3b6290e95&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a560aca3f99b145384c2b736c2ceea1c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c4d75b2c01d2448f37de4deec12208fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2173942c84747feba52cff952903a7f5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
