<node id="Monitoring and Evaluation">
  <data key="d0">Monitoring and Evaluation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Monitoring and evaluation involve assessing the effectiveness of educational programmes and patient knowledge regarding diabetic neuropathy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-55d2691a8c714949752d249721fec5e7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850009</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Lower-Limb Amputations">
  <data key="d0">Lower-Limb Amputations</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Lower-limb amputations refer to the surgical removal of legs or feet, with statistics showing that diabetes significantly increases the risk.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-55d2691a8c714949752d249721fec5e7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850009</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hospitalization">
  <data key="d0">Hospitalization</data>
  <data key="d1">event</data>
  <data key="d2">Hospitalization refers to the period when a patient is admitted to a hospital for the treatment of infections or surgical procedures such as amputations, which can last several weeks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-55d2691a8c714949752d249721fec5e7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850009</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nephropathy">
  <data key="d0">Nephropathy</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Nephropathy is a complication of diabetes that affects the kidneys, which should be carefully monitored particularly when considering angiography due to renal deterioration risks.&lt;SEP&gt;Nephropathy is a medical condition affecting the kidneys, which may be exacerbated by the administration of radiopaque dye during angiography.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-55d2691a8c714949752d249721fec5e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-56d9ff3515afac60e7566e41837249a0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850009</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Acarbose">
  <data key="d0">Acarbose</data>
  <data key="d1">drug</data>
  <data key="d2">Acarbose is an α-glucosidase inhibitor with a recommended dosage of 100–300 mg/day to delay carbohydrate absorption.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850009</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Miglitol">
  <data key="d0">Miglitol</data>
  <data key="d1">drug</data>
  <data key="d2">Miglitol is an α-glucosidase inhibitor similar to acarbose, also recommended at 100–300 mg/day to delay carbohydrate absorption.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Short-Acting Insulin">
  <data key="d0">Short-Acting Insulin</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Short-acting insulin, such as regular/semilente, has an onset of action of 15–30 minutes and a duration of 5–7 hours.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Intermediate-Acting Insulin">
  <data key="d0">Intermediate-Acting Insulin</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Intermediate-acting insulin, such as NPH/lente, has an onset of 2–4 hours and lasts for 18–24 hours.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Long-Acting Insulin">
  <data key="d0">Long-Acting Insulin</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Long-acting insulin, like ultralente, starts working in 4–5 hours and can last up to 36 hours.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mixed Insulin">
  <data key="d0">Mixed Insulin</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Mixed insulin consists of regular/NPH blends with varying action times aimed at providing a balance in insulin delivery.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Insulin Analogs">
  <data key="d0">Insulin Analogs</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Insulin analogs are modified forms of insulin designed to provide faster or longer durations of action compared to regular insulin.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-453e4228f98ddea76e07ce405d13fd32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769850010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
